english:
  title: Memorial to the Commander-in-Chief on Proper Rites for the War Dead
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, I, Lee, humble recorder of military affairs and keeper of provisions, respectfully submit this memorial to the Commander-in-Chief and Vice Minister of War.

    Though my station is lowly and my voice often falters like one bereft of speech, when justice demands utterance, I cannot remain silent. How could I suppress what must be spoken in the council of war, where many minds gather to weigh the greatest matters? Whether you heed my words rests with your wisdom alone—I would not presume to hide behind false silence.

    The generals of old knew well that sharp blades matter less than soldiers' hearts. When the will of the troops dissolves, what use are ten thousand strong warriors? This is why commanders share both hardship and comfort with their men.

    Tang Taizong, campaigning in distant lands, saw his general Li Simo struck by an arrow. The emperor himself drew out the poison with his lips. Upon returning, he gathered the bones of the fallen, prepared great offerings, and wept with such grief that every soldier shed tears and burned with resolve. When the father of Nan Chengsi died at Suiyang, the boy—still in swaddling clothes—was elevated in rank. Later, when campaigning in the west, Chengsi himself begged to lead a unit and offer his life for the cause. I have read these passages and could not set down my book for my tears.

    Consider even a humble man: though he dies on a sickbed in the hands of women, his descendants will beg for grain to prepare his funeral feast, will dig the earth to make his tomb. How much more should we honor the great-hearted warrior who marches ten thousand miles, who stands unbowed as arrows fall like rain, who fights with all his strength unto death in service to his lord? Such a death is infinitely more noble than perishing in bed. Yet far from home, he dies a stranger in distant lands. Though he has sons and grandsons, how swiftly can they gather? This is why the ancients collected the bones of the fallen and performed rites—because the spirit, even in death, knows and remembers.

    Even should the soul lack consciousness, drifting in darkness, the very fact of death in the lord's service commands our reverence. And truly, the five essences and seven forms of man persist beyond death. If honored with the gathering of bones and offerings of sacrifice, would not the spirit dance and rejoice beneath the earth as if still living?

    I hear that at Xunyang, many of our soldiers fell fighting valiantly. Their bones lie scattered on the field, uncollected. No grain from the official stores has been distributed for their remembrance. No order has gone forth to gather and bury them. No record has been made of their valor. This departs grievously from the way of our ancestors. This is why I dare raise my voice in protest.

    I humbly beseech the Commander-in-Chief and Vice Minister: issue a decree throughout the army. Let the bones of the fallen be gathered without distinction—we cannot tell one man's remains from another's, and why should we divide them by rank or allegiance? The Record of Rites teaches that in spring we cover exposed bones and bury scattered remains, for we wish not to wound heaven's harmony. Now is that season; the burial of bones accords with righteousness, and how much more for those who died for their country?

    For each fallen soldier, provide grain from the official stores proportionate to the number of dead, so that their spirits may be invoked and honored. Record the deeds of the most valiant among them in the annals, that their descendants may receive reward. Then not only will the spirits below weep with gratitude and harbor thoughts of repayment—but the living soldiers of this army, seeing such honor given to the fallen, will be stirred to such fury and courage that one man among them will be worth a thousand.

    Behold: to honor the dead is to inspire the living. This is no trivial matter of state. I most humbly beseech you to consider it carefully. My position carries responsibility for counsel; I cannot remain silent. In my presumption, I have overstepped the bounds of respect, and I present this memorial with deepest deference.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Xunyang (巘陽): The site of a military engagement, likely during the Goryeo period when this memorial was written.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Li Simo (李思摩): A historical general under Tang Taizong known for his loyalty and valor.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Nan Chengsi (南承嗣): A historical figure whose father died defending Suiyang, exemplifying the sacrifice discussed in the memorial.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Record of Rites (禮記), Monthly Ordinances (月令): A classical Confucian text prescribing seasonal rituals, invoked here to justify proper burial rites.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Five essences and seven forms (五精七魄): A concept from traditional Chinese cosmology describing the components of the human spirit that persist after death.'
